[[File:3145 - Vaduz - Pasta vom Schützengarten (cropped).jpg|230px|thumb|A dish from the Protector's Garden café in [[Vaduz]], [[Liechtenstein]]]]
'''Liechtensteiner cuisine''' is the cuisine of [[Liechtenstein]]. The cuisine is diverse and has been influenced by the [[cuisine]] of nearby countries, particularly [[Swiss cuisine|Switzerland]] and [[Austrian cuisine|Austria]],<ref name="LP">{{cite book |title=Western Europe 8th Edition |last=Ver Berkmoes |first=Ryan |authorlink= |year=2007 |publisher=Lonely Planet |location= |isbn=1741042348 |page=825 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jt98hroM0UUC&pg=PA825&dq=Liechtensteiner+cuisine&hl=en&sa=X&ei=PnbqUOD7GOGmiQLdx4GgCA&ved=0CEcQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Liechtensteiner%20cuisine&f=false |accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref><ref name="WC"/> and is also influenced by [[European cuisine|Central European cuisine]].<ref name="gowealthy">[http://www.gowealthy.com/gowealthy/wcms/en/home/articles/travel/food-and-beverage/Cuisine-of-Liechtenstein-OV341ze1KU.html "Cuisine of Liechtenstein."] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928131015/http://www.gowealthy.com/gowealthy/wcms/en/home/articles/travel/food-and-beverage/Cuisine-of-Liechtenstein-OV341ze1KU.html |date=2011-09-28 }} [http://www.gowealthy.com Gowealthy.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100807024951/http://www.gowealthy.com/ |date=2010-08-07 }}. Accessed July 30, 2011.</ref> Cheeses and soups are integral parts of Liechtensteiner cuisine.<ref name="LP"/> Milk products are also commonplace in the country's cuisine, due to an expansive [[Dairy|dairy industry]].<ref name="WC">{{cite book |title=The World Cookbook for Students, Volume 1 |last=Jacob |first=Jeanne |authorlink= |author2=Ashkenazi, Michael |year=2007 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |location= |isbn=0313334552 |page= |pages=110–111 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LohMBqO3nBYC&pg=RA2-PA110&dq=Liechtensteiner+cuisine&hl=en&sa=X&ei=BXfqUNaGMMa5igLL-ICgAQ&ved=0CDYQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=Liechtensteiner%20cuisine&f=false |accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref> Common vegetables include greens, potatoes and cabbage.<ref name="WC"/> Widely consumed meats include beef, chicken and pork.<ref name="WC"/> The consumption of three meals a day is commonplace, and meals are often formal.<ref name="WC"/>
==Common foods and dishes== [[File:Muesli.jpg|thumb|[[Muesli]] is a common breakfast dish in Liechtensteiner cuisine<ref name="WC"/>]] * [[Asparagus]] is frequently used * Bread<ref name="WC"/> * Hafalaab{{spaced ndash}} a [[soup]] with [[ham]] or [[bacon]] and [[cornmeal]] [[dumpling]]s<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.studycountry.com/guide/LI-gastronomy.htm|title=Gastronomy in Liechtenstein|website=Studycountry|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> * [[Kasknopfl]]{{spaced ndash}} small dumplings topped with cheese or [[onion]]s<ref name="gowealthy"/><ref name="europetoday">[http://europe-today.com/liechtenstein/liechtenstein-cuisine.html "Liechtenstein Cuisine."] [http://europe-today.com Europe-today.com]. Accessed July 30, 2011.</ref> * [[Liver (food)|Liver]]<ref name="WC"/> * [[Muesli]]<ref name="WC"/>{{spaced ndash}} uncooked [[rolled oats]], fruit and nuts that have been soaked in water or juice * [[Pastry|Pastries]]<ref name="WC"/> * Ribel{{spaced ndash}} a [[grain]]<ref name="gowealthy"/> * [[Rösti]]<ref name="LP"/>{{spaced ndash}} a dish prepared with coarsely grated potato that is fried. It may include regional variations that utilize additional ingredients * [[Sandwich]]es<ref name="WC"/> * [[Saukerkas]]{{spaced ndash}} a [[cheese]] produced in Liechtenstein * [[Schnitzel]]{{spaced ndash}} a [[breaded cutlet]] dish made with boneless meat thinned with a mallet. * [[Smoked meat]]s * Torkarebl{{spaced ndash}} a [[porridge]] dish that resembles dumplings * [[Sausage|Wurst]]{{spaced ndash}} smoked sausages<ref name="LP"/> * [[Yogurt]]<ref name="WC"/>
