{{expand German|Sathmarer Schwaben|date=August 2012}}

The '''Satu Mare Swabians''' or '''Sathmar Swabians'''<ref name="Barcan"/><ref name="Steigerwald"/> (German: '''Sathmarer Schwaben''') are a [[Germans|German]] ethnic group in the [[Satu Mare]] region of [[Romania]].<ref name="Barcan">Monica Barcan, Adalbert Millitz, ''The German Nationality in Romania'' (1978), page 42: "The Satu Mare Swabians are true Swabians, their place of origin being Wurttemberg. They were colonized between 1712 and 1815. Their most important settlements are Satu Mare/Sathmar and Petresti/Petrifeld in North- West Romania."</ref> They are one of the few [[Danube Swabian]] subgroups that are actually [[Swabia]]n,<ref name="Barcan"/> and their dialect, [[Sathmar Swabian]], is similar to other varieties of [[Swabian German|Swabian]].

Most were originally farmers in Upper [[Swabia]] who came to [[Partium]] (at the time [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]], now Romania) during the [[East Colonisation]] in the 1700s.<ref name="Barcan"/> Their principal settlements were [[Satu Mare|Satu Mare (Sathmar)]], [[Carei|Carei (Karol)]], [[Petrești, Satu Mare|Petrești (Petrifeld)]],<ref name="Barcan"/> and [[Foieni|Foieni (Fienen)]], and they also inhabited [[Urziceni, Satu Mare|Urziceni]] (Schinal), [[Căpleni]] (Kaplau), [[Tiream]] (Terem), [[Beltiug]] (Bildegg), [[Ciumești]] (Schamagosch), and [[Ardud]] (Erdeed).

After the [[Second World War]], many evacuated, migrated or were expelled to [[Germany]].<ref name="Steigerwald">Jacob Steigerwald, ''Tracing Romania's heterogeneous German minority from its origins to the Diaspora'' (1985), page 14: "Since the final stages of WWII, Romania has not been the only country where substantial groups of Sathmar Swabians can be found. For over thirty-five years now, there has been a growing community of Sathmar Swabians in West Germany also."</ref> Those that remain in Romania, along with other German-speaking groups in Romania, are represented in politics by the DFDR ([[Democratic Forum of Germans in Romania]]).

